      "side": 1,
      "message": "IF \u0027${exist}\u0027 \u003d\u003d \u0027${False}\u0027 — fragile boolean comparison\n\n${exist} is assigned from Evaluate ${resource_name} in ${present_names}, which returns a Python bool. Comparing \u0027${exist}\u0027 (string-interpolated) to \u0027${False}\u0027 (string \"False\") works in practice because RF serialises False as \"False\", but it is non-idiomatic and fragile. A more idiomatic and explicit check is:\n\n```\nIF  not ${exist}\n```\n\nThe not ${exist} form directly evaluates the boolean without string coercion, is easier to read, and is consistent with the existing Skip If not ${has_resources} pattern already used in the same test case (line 103).",
      "revId": "74a2459f1ff2792ea979fe9fc81c2f440a12e7af",
